{[%evp 0,9,36,20,36,5,37,37,37,37,37,12]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4
d6 5. Bg5 {A rare move. Normally White waits for 0-0 and then plays this move.}
h6 $1 {I believe this is the best reaction! Black immediately asks where
white's bishop will go.} ({The other options are:} 5... c5 6. dxc5 $1 Qa5 7.
Bd2 Qxc5 (7... dxc5 {Still a bit worse for Black after:} 8. e5 Nfd7 9. f4 Nc6
10. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Rg7] The bishop on g7 is out of the play. White should have
some advantage here.}) 8. h3 $1 {Important prophylactic move.} ({In case of} 8.
Nf3 {Black will continue with} Ng4 $1 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gc5f2] White already
have some problems with the f2 pawn.} 9. Qe2 Nc6 10. h3 Nge5 $132 {Black has a
lot of counterplay.}) 8... O-O 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. Rc1 {With a couple of accurate
moves, White will manage to have some small plus.} Be6 11. b3 a5 12. Bd3 Nd7
13. O-O $14 {White has some space advantage, and Black still needs to work for
equality.}) (5... O-O {The most played move.} 6. Qd2 {This is a big theory,
and also possible for Black. In any case, the main move is the better one!}) 6.
Be3 ({Worse is:} 6. Bh4 $6 c5 $1 {With the bishop on h4 in many lines White
will not have the move Bg5-d2.} 7. dxc5 (7. d5 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ga5e1]} 8.
Qd2 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Prepares b5.} 9. a4 Nbd7 10. Ra3 Nh5 $132 {[%cal Gg6g5]
Black has the initiative. The threat is g5 with the idea to exchange the
bishop on g3.}) 7... Qa5 {That's why Black included h6-Bh4. Now the move
Bg5-d2 is not possible.} 8. Qd2 dxc5 $1 ({Worse is:} 8... Qxc5 9. f3 {[%cal
Gh4f2]}) 9. Bxf6 ({White is much worse after:} 9. e5 $6 Ng4 10. Nd5 Qxd2+ 11.
Kxd2 Na6 $17) 9... exf6 10. Nd5 Qxd2+ 11. Kxd2 Na6 {The endgame definitely is
very pleasant for Black. The pair of bishops gives Black a slight advantage.}
12. Bd3 Be6 13. Ne2 O-O-O 14. Rad1 h5 $15 {[%csl Ge6,Gg7] Black will not hurry
with the move f6-f5. Fro Now the plan is Rhe8 and eventually Na6-b4-c6.}) 6...
Ng4 $1 {It is very important to play energetically.} 7. Bc1 (7. Bf4 {This move
looks strange. After:} e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 $132 {Black has a fantastic game.}) 7...
c5 $1 {The best way to continue. Black wants to keep the diagonal a1-h8 open
for his bishop.} ({Also possible, but a bit worse is:} 7... e5 8. d5 f5 9. f3
Nf6 10. exf5 gxf5 11. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gg1e2,Ge2g3] White keeps some
small plus.}) 8. dxc5 ({In case of} 8. d5 {very strong is} Bd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4]}
9. Nh3 {The only move.} e5 $5 {[%csl Gd4] I like the idea to keep the bishop
on d for now.} ({Another option is:} 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nf6 {[%csl Re4,Rh3]
[%cal Gf6e4,Gc8h3]} 11. Qc2 Bxh3 12. gxh3 Nbd7 $132 {This position is very
double-edged. White's pawn structure is terrible, but the pair of bishops
compensates for it.}) 10. g3 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gb8a6] The plan is Na6-f5.
Black has good counter chances.}) 8... Bxc3+ {A typical idea.} ({Also good is:
} 8... dxc5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bd2 (10. h3 Bxc3+ {Transpose}) 10... Bd4 11. Nd1
Be6 $11) 9. bxc3 dxc5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4] The endgame is
approximately equal, but from a practical point of view I definitely prefer
Black.} 11. h3 {The most logical move here.} ({The other moves do not change
much.} 11. f3 Nf6) (11. Nf3 Nc6 12. Bf4 g5 13. Bg3 Nf6 $132 {[%csl Rc4,Re4]
[%cal Gf6e4]}) 11... Nf6 12. e5 {Gaining more space.} ({A bit worse is:} 12.
Bd3 Nc6 13. f4 b6 14. Nf3 Kc7 $15 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc8a6,Gc6a5] The pawn on c
can be a real target.}) 12... Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8c7] I think the best move. The
knight will come to c7.} 13. Bf4 ({A bit worse is:} 13. Be3 b6 14. O-O-O+ Kc7
15. Bf4 Be6 $15 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb8c6,Gc6a5]}) 13... Nc7 14. O-O-O+ Ke8 15.
Nf3 Nc6 16. Be2 Ne6 17. Bg3 Nf8 $5 {[%cal Gc8e6] A very nice idea. The point
is to place the bishop on e6.} (17... Bd7 18. Nd2) 18. Nd2 Be6 19. f4 Rd8 20.
Bf3 g5 $132 {[%cal Gf8g6] The knight from f8 will finally find his place.} *

