{[%evp 0,9,28,17,29,-10,37,37,37,36,31,8]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4
d6 5. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2g3] A rare move, compared to the main lines, but quite
popular in recent years. Many strong players tried to play this set-up for
White. The main idea is to place the knight to g3 and eventually to push h2-h4.
} O-O 6. Ng3 h5 $1 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gh5h4] A very logical move in my opinion.
For now, it is not clear if it is better for Black to push e7-e5 or to look
for c7-c5. Because of this, I think it is better to postpone both and wait for
White's reaction. The point of h5 is also that White should decide immediately
how to develop his pieces, to push h2-h4 or not.} ({By far the most played
move is:} 6... e5 7. d5 a5 8. h4 h5 9. Bg5 Qe8 10. Be2 Na6 11. Qd2 $14 {
We can find a lot of games in this position, some of them at a very top level.
I think the position is still unclear, but I slightly prefer White.}) ({
Another option is to play in a Benoni style with..} 6... c5 7. d5 e6 8. Be2
exd5 9. cxd5 {We can find a lot of games in this position.} Re8 10. O-O $14 {
It is a very popular and played position, however, the games show that White
has better chances to have the advantage.}) 7. Be2 {Probably the best move.} ({
The other options are:} 7. Bd3 {It is worse compare to Be2.} h4 8. Nge2 h3 $1
9. gxh3 ({Now very bad is:} 9. g3 $2 {in view of} Bg4 $17 {[%csl Rf3][%cal
Gg4f3] Black is much better. The control of f3 square will be very unpleasant
for White.}) 9... Nc6 10. Rg1 e5 $132 {Of course is still not clear, but Black
got everything possible. White should be extremely careful here.}) (7. Bg5 {
Another logical move. Stops h5-h4 for now.} Nh7 8. Be3 c5 $1 {Black does not
want to rush with the push h5-h4.} 9. dxc5 {Taking the pawn.} (9. d5 e6 $132 {
[%cal Gh5h4] Now the Benoni-like position looks good for Black.}) 9... dxc5 10.
Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Bxc5 Nc6 {[%cal Gh5h4] In this kind of position Black always
have a very nice compensation for the pawn. White lacks development.} 12. h4 {
Otherwise h5-h4 was already a threat.} Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6]} 13. Be2 b6 14. Be3
Ne6 $44 {[%cal Ge6d4,Gc8a6] Black has a fantastic compensation for the pawn.
For example after 15.0-0 Black can even play Bf6 to attack the h pawn.}) (7. h4
Nc6 $1 {This is the point! Now Black still didn't play e5, and the square e5
can be used from black's knight.} 8. d5 ({If} 8. Bg5 {then} e5 {[%csl Rd4]
[%cal Gc6d4] Taking the control over d4 square.}) 8... Ne5 {[%csl Ge5,Rg4]
With h5-h4 included the Black knight on e5 is untouchable.} 9. Be2 c6 $1 {
Opening another front.} ({Worse is:} 9... e6 $6 10. Bg5 exd5 11. cxd5 c6 12.
Qd2 $14 {1-0 (27) Kim,S (2295) -Jones,G (2671) Chess.com INT 2022}) 10. Bg5 Bg4
$5 {A bit provocative move.} ({Also possible is:} 10... Bd7 11. Qd2 a5 $132)
11. f3 Bd7 {[%cal Ga7g1] Now Black hopes to use the g1-a7 diagonal.} 12. Qd2
cxd5 13. cxd5 b5 $132 {Black has the initiative.}) 7... a5 $1 {A very rare
move! The idea is still to postpone the decision of playing c5 or e5. It seems
that White does not have useful waiting moves.} ({The other options are worse:
} 7... h4 8. Nf1) (7... e5 8. d5) 8. Be3 {A very logical move.} (8. h4 {
This is very similar to 7.h4} Nc6 $1 9. Bg5 Nh7 ({Here also possible is to
prepare e7-e5 with} 9... Re8 $5) 10. Be3 e5 11. d5 Nd4 $132 {[%csl Gd4] The
knight on d is very powerful.}) (8. Bg5 Nh7 9. Be3 e5 {Here Black is already
for this push.} 10. d5 h4 11. Nf1 f5 12. h3 Na6 $132 {Black has a fantastic
King's indian defence game.}) (8. h3 {Stops eventually h4-h3.} Na6 9. Bg5 (9.
Be3 {Does not change much after:} e5 10. d5 Nc5 $132 {[%cal Gh5h4]}) 9... Nh7
10. Be3 e5 11. d5 h4 12. Nf1 f5 $132) (8. f3 {A bit strange move, but has his
logic. The idea is to be ready for h5-h4 and just in case to protect the pawn
on e4.} a4 $5 {Black has also other good options, but I really like this idea.
Definitely, Black has the initiative.} 9. Nxa4 ({Worse is:} 9. Be3 $6 {in view
of} c5 $1 {[%cal Gg7a1]} 10. d5 a3 {[%cal Gg7a1] White has some problems on
the a1-h8 diagonal.} 11. b3 Ng4 $1 12. fxg4 Bxc3+ 13. Bd2 Bxa1 14. Qxa1 h4 15.
Nf1 Nd7 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd7e5,Gf7f6] The knight on e5 will be very strong.
}) 9... h4 10. Nf1 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] Black is using the fact that White still
didn't develop his pieces.} 11. d5 {Probably the most critical line.} ({
In case of} 11. Be3 e5 12. d5 Nd4 $132 {[%csl Gd4] Black has a fantastic
initiative.}) (11. Nc3 {Another option, a bit better than 11.Be3, but still
Black has a serious initiative.} e5 12. dxe5 {Going for the endgame looks like
a decent decision.} (12. d5 Nd4 13. Bg5 h3 14. g4 c6 $132 {[%cal Gd8b6]}) 12...
dxe5 ({Also interesting is:} 12... h3 $5) 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6d4]
The square d4 gives Black an excellent play.} 14. Bg5 Nd4 15. Kf2 h3 16. g4 c6
$44 {[%csl Gd4] I really like Black's chances here. The knight on d4 gives
Black an excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 11... Nd4 $1 12. Qxd4 Rxa4 {
Black is a pawn up, but it is clear for White will be not easy to properly
develop his pieces.} 13. Qd1 ({Another option is:} 13. Qf2 c6 14. Ne3 cxd5 15.
cxd5 e6 {Black wants immediately to open the position.} 16. dxe6 Bxe6 17. Qxh4
d5 $132 {Black's initiative compensates the sacrificed pawns.}) 13... Bd7 14.
a3 ({If} 14. Ne3 {then} Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5f4,Gg7a1]}) 14... Ra8 {[%cal Gc7c6]
Prepares c6.} 15. Ne3 c6 16. O-O ({Another option is:} 16. dxc6 bxc6 17. O-O
Qb8 $44 {[%cal Gb8b2,Ga8a3] Black has a nice compensation.}) 16... cxd5 17.
cxd5 Qb6 18. Kh1 Ba4 19. Qe1 Rfc8 $44 {[%cal Gc8c1] I like very much Black's
perspectives.}) (8. O-O e5 {Black is not in hurry to push h4.} 9. d5 {The
standard response.} (9. dxe5 {More direct approach.} dxe5 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Bg5
Rd7 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] Prepares Nc6 next.} 12. Nd5 Nh7 13. Be3 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6,
Gb8c6] Very soon Black will control completely the d4 square.}) 9... Na6 10. h3
Nh7 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gf7f5] Black is doing very well. The plan is to push h4 and
then f5.}) 8... a4 $1 {A very nice approach. White must resolve some concrete
issues now.} 9. O-O ({Of course not} 9. Nxa4 $2 {because of} h4 10. Nf1 Nxe4
$17 {with a big advantage for Black.}) (9. a3 {Stops a4-a3,but gives up the b3
square.} Bd7 10. f3 h4 11. Nf1 Nc6 12. d5 Na5 $132 {[%csl Rb3] Black has an
excellent play.}) 9... h4 ({Similar is} 9... c5) 10. Nh1 c5 11. dxc5 {The most
principled.} ({In case of} 11. d5 h3 12. g3 e6 $132 {Black has an excellent
Benoni type of position.}) 11... dxc5 12. Bxc5 ({The other options are:} 12.
Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Bxc5 Nc6 14. Rad1 Be6 $132 {All Black's pieces are working very
well.}) (12. e5 {Black is completely fine after:} Qxd1 13. Raxd1 Ng4 14. Bxc5
Bxe5 15. f4 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nc6 $11 {The endgame looks approximately equal.})
12... Nc6 13. f4 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gh1f2]} Qa5 {Black already keeps the queens.} 14.
Ba3 {Otherwise a4-a3 can be unpleasant.} Rd8 15. Qe1 Bg4 $1 {Black has the
initiative, but the game is still very concrete.} 16. Bxg4 ({The other option
is:} 16. e5 Bxe2 17. Nxe2 Ng4 $44 {[%cal Gg4e3] Black has very unpleasant
threats.}) 16... Nxg4 17. e5 Qa7+ {Provokes c5.} 18. c5 {The only move. After
18.Nf2 Black will respond with Ne3.} Qa6 $1 {[%cal Ga6c4] Black is using all
his forces.} 19. h3 Nh6 20. Qxh4 Nf5 21. Qf2 Rd3 {[%csl Ra3,Gd3,Rh1] Black
lost 2 pawns,but definitely has the initiative. White's pieces are lacking
coordination.} 22. Rad1 Rad8 23. Qe2 Qc4 $44 {The game is still very sharp,
but it looks like Black is having all the fun. All Black's pieces are
perfectly placed.} *

