{[%evp 0,9,29,32,29,-1,37,41,55,55,36,23]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4
d6 5. f4 {Four pawns system. This system was very popular in the 80s and 90s.
When I was a kid this was my favourite system against King's Indian Defence.
Nowadays the modern theory suggests that Black has a couple of options, which
leads to a nice game.} O-O 6. Nf3 c5 {I like to suggest this move. I think is
the most principled and logical continuation.} ({Another very big line is:} 
6... Na6 {Played by many strong players including Garry Kasparov.} 7. Bd3 $5 {
I believe this is the problem for Black after 6...Na6.} ({Another main move is:
} 7. Be2) 7... e5 8. fxe5 dxe5 9. d5 c6 10. O-O $14 {I think here, Black still
should fight for equality.}) 7. d5 {The obvious move. All other moves are very
strange for White:} (7. e5 $6 {Not a good move.} Nfd7 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Re5] Here
White has a big problem keeping his centre together.}) (7. Be2 {A bit rare
move.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 e5 $1 {The best way to continue. Black immediately
challenges White's pieces in the centre.} ({By far the most played move is:} 
8... Nc6 9. Be3 Bg4 {The most direct approach. Of course, Black has other
options, but then White will simply castle with a small advantage.} 10. Nxc6
Bxe2 11. Nxd8 Bxd1 12. Rxd1 Rfxd8 13. b3 $14 {After all exchanges White still
keeps some small plus in the endgame.}) 9. Ndb5 {[%csl Rd6] The most logical
reply. Attack the pawn on d6.} ({After:} 9. fxe5 dxe5 10. Ndb5 Nc6 {Black is
doing fine. For example:} 11. Qxd8 (11. Be3 Be6 $11) (11. O-O Nd4 {[%csl Gd4]
Black has a nice play already. The game can continue:} 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Be6
14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Nd5 g5 16. Bf2 Nxe4 17. Bxd4 Bxd5 18. cxd5 Qxd5 19. Bxg7 Qxd1
20. Raxd1 Kxg7 21. Rd7 $11 {White's active pieces compensate the pawn. The
endgame should be very equal.}) 11... Rxd8 12. O-O h6 $1 {It is very important
to stop Bg5.} 13. Nc7 Rb8 14. Be3 Nd4 $11 {The endgame should be equal, but I
prefer Black's chances.}) 9... Ne8 $1 {A bit passive,but necessary.} ({Worse
is:} 9... Nc6 $6 10. O-O) 10. fxe5 ({Much worse is:} 10. c5 $2 Nc6 $17) ({
Another option is:} 10. Nd5 Nc6 11. O-O exf4 12. Bxf4 Bxb2 13. Rb1 Be5 14. Qd2
Be6 $132 {White has some compensation, but Black is definitely not worse and
finding for the advantage.}) 10... Bxe5 $11 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gb8c6,Gd8h4] The
bishop on e5 is extremely strong.}) (7. dxc5 {Another popular move.} Na6 $1 {
Very rare, but clearly the best move. Black is taking the initiative.} ({
I believe also ok is:} 7... dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. e5 Ne8 10. Be3 b6 11. Nd5 Nc6
12. O-O-O Bb7 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf7f6] The endgame is about equal. Black's plan
is to push f6 in the right moment.}) (7... Qa5 {Main Theory} 8. Bd3 Qxc5 9. Qe2
{This is a very popular position with many games played. I do believe that the
main move is the better one.}) 8. cxd6 {To take the pawn looks reasonable.
Otherwise Black will just play Nxc5 with a good game.} exd6 9. e5 {Provoking
the endgame.} ({Another critical move is:} 9. Bd3 Qb6 $1 {I like this approach.
Keeping the king in the centre.} ({Also good is:} 9... Nc5 10. O-O Re8 11. Qc2
({After:} 11. Re1 Qb6 12. Kf1 Bd7 $44 {[%cal Ga8c8] Black has an excellent
play for the game.}) 11... Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Nxe4 {This leads to mass exchanges.}
13. Nxe4 Bf5 14. Re1 Qb6+ 15. Be3 ({If} 15. Kf1 {then} Qc6 {[%csl Re4]}) 15...
Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Rxe4 17. Bxb6 Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1 axb6 $11 {The endgame is at least
equal for Black.}) 10. Na4 ({Worse is:} 10. Qe2 $6 {[%cal Gc1e3] In view of}
Nc5 11. Bc2 Bf5 $1 $17 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf8e8] Black takes the advantage.})
10... Qc6 11. Nd4 Qe8 {[%csl Re4]} 12. O-O ({If} 12. Nc3 $6 {then} Bg4 {
White's queen doesn't have a good place.}) 12... Nxe4 13. Nb5 Nb4 14. Bb1 Qc6
15. a3 Na6 $132 {[%cal Ga6c5] Definitely,White should be careful.}) 9... dxe5
10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. fxe5 ({Much worse is:} 11. Nxe5 $2 Nb4 12. Kf2 Ng4+ 13. Nxg4
Bxg4 14. h3 Bd4+ 15. Kg3 Bf5 $17 {[%cal Gb4c2] Black's pieces are very active.}
) 11... Ng4 12. Bf4 Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c2]} 13. Rc1 Nc6 {Black will return the
pawn with a very pleasant endgame.} 14. Be2 Ngxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Bxe5 Nxe5
17. b3 Bf5 $11) 7... e6 8. Be2 {The main move.} (8. e5 $6 {A dubious move. I
believe Black is already better after:} dxe5 9. fxe5 Ng4 10. Bg5 ({If} 10. Bf4
$6 {then} Nd7 $17 {[%csl Re5]}) 10... Qb6 11. Qe2 (11. Qd2 {Does nor change
much.} Nd7 12. O-O-O Ndxe5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 $17) 11... Nd7 12. Bf4 f6 $1 $15 {
[%csl Re1] White has big problems with his central pawns and the king.}) (8.
Bd3 {A quite logical move. There is a small, but significant difference
compare to 8.Be2.} exd5 9. cxd5 b5 $1 {With the bishop on d3,this move works
perfectly.} 10. e5 ({The other moves are very harmless:} 10. Bxb5 Nxe4 {
The typical trick.} 11. Nxe4 Qa5+ 12. Kf2 Qxb5 13. Nxd6 Qb6 14. Nc4 (14. Nxc8
Rxc8 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rd5,Rf2][%cal Gc8d8]}) 14... Qa6 15. Qe2 Nd7 16. Rd1 Nf6
$15 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc8b7,Gf8e8] Black has a serious initiative.}) (10. Nxb5
Re8 $15 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gc8f5]}) 10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Ng4 {The same position with
the bishop on e2 is also a big theory. After 12.Bg5 Qb6 the position remains
very double-edged, but the theory proves that White has a bit better chances.
Here, with the bishop on d3 is different, because Black has the move c5-c4
with a tempo.} 12. Bxb5 ({In case of} 12. Bg5 $6 Qb6 {Now White can't castle.
This is the big difference between Be2 and Bd3.} 13. Bxb5 Nxe5 $15 {[%csl Rb2]
[%cal Ga7a6] Black is better.}) 12... Nxe5 13. O-O {I think the position
remains very balanced. Black has no problems at all, but White keeps the
equality.} a6 ({Another option is:} 13... Bg4 14. Be2 Nbd7 15. Nxe5 Bxe2 16.
Qxe2 Nxe5 17. Bf4 Qb6 $11 {[%cal Ga8e8]}) 14. Nxe5 (14. Be2 Nbd7 $132) 14...
Bxe5 15. Ba4 {Here Black is invited to force a perpetual check.} Qh4 {Leads to
a draw.} ({Worse is:} 15... Nd7 $6 16. Bf4 $14) 16. g3 Bxg3 17. hxg3 Qxg3+ 18.
Kh1 Qh3+ $11) (8. dxe6 {Another big move. Recently this line was tried by some
strong players. For example, D.Dubov tried it in a very high level.} fxe6 $1 ({
Worse is:} 8... Bxe6 $6 9. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5,Ge1g1]}) 9. Bd3 {The most
natural way to develop the bishop.} ({Of course not good is:} 9. e5 $6 {
because the endgame after:} dxe5 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. fxe5 (11. Nxe5 Nfd7 $15)
11... Ng4 12. Bg5 Rd7 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gb8c6] is clearly in Black's favour.
}) (9. g3 {A rare move. Tried recently by D.Dubov.} Nc6 10. Bg2 e5 $1 {[%csl
Rd4][%cal Gc6d4] A nice positional move. Black is taking control over the
d4-square. The position looks very balanced.} 11. fxe5 (11. O-O Bg4 $132) 11...
dxe5 (11... Ng4 $5 {Maybe also makes sense.}) 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. O-O ({Another
option is:} 13. Bg5 {This position occurred in the game Dubov, D (2702) -Hua,
L (2305) Chess.com INT 2022. Here Black could equalize easily after:} h6 14.
Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd5 Rf8 $11) 13... b6 14. Nd5 Rf8 15. Bg5 Ne8 {A bit passive,
but for now is important to protect everything.} 16. b3 Rb8 $11 {[%cal Gb8b7,
Gb7f7] The endgame is equal.}) (9. Be2 {Also possible, but in my opinion a bit
worse than 9.Bd3.} Nc6 10. O-O b6 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc8b7,Gd8e7] With the
bishop on e2, this plan looks very reasonable.} 11. Kh1 Bb7 12. Be3 Qd7 13. Qd2
