{[%evp 0,9,58,35,27,0,39,38,37,29,29,14]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4
d6 5. Bd3 {[%cal Gg1e2] A very positional and interesting set-up. White's main
idea is to put the knight on e2 and then to castle. After that very often the
knight goes to g3. This system is known to be very solid for White, and
practically Black has almost no chance for a direct attack on the king's side.}
O-O 6. Nge2 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge7e5] One of the main moves together with 6..
.e5 and 6...c5. I think this is the most natural move here. Black is fighting
for the d4 square. Of course one of the main points is that 7.d5 will be met
by Ne5 with the idea to play c6 and to exchange the knight with the bishop on
d3.} ({The other main options are:} 6... e5 {I am not a big fan of this plan
here. The main difference is that with the knight on e2 White can fight very
easy with the typical push f7-f5 by taking on f5 and then play either f2-f4 or
f2-f3 with the idea Qc2 and Ng3 to attack the pawn on f5.} 7. d5 Nh5 {[%cal
Gf7f5] One of the most common plans.} ({Another theoretical line is:} 7... a5
8. O-O Na6 9. f3) 8. O-O f5 9. exf5 $1 {In the line with Bd3-Nge2 almost
always on f5 White reacts with exf5.} gxf5 10. Ng3 $1 {[%csl Rh5] A very nice
idea. I don't see clear equality for Black here.} Nxg3 ({If} 10... Nf4 {then}
11. Bxf4 exf4 12. Nh5 $1 {[%csl Rf4,Rg7]}) 11. fxg3 $14 {[%csl Rf5] White has
an easy game.}) (6... c5 {This is my second favourite option.} 7. d5 e6 8. O-O
({Another big theory is:} 8. Bg5 exd5 9. exd5) 8... exd5 9. cxd5 {This is a
huge theory. White's plan normally goes Ng3-and the to look for f2-f4 or first
Bg5. This position is very playable for both sides, but according to the
latest games it seems a bit easier to play with the white pieces.}) 7. O-O ({
White also tried other moves, but they don't lead to anything special. For
example after:} 7. Bg5 e5 8. d5 Nd4 {[%csl Gd4]} 9. Qd2 c5 10. O-O Bd7 $11 {
[%cal Ga7a6] Black has an equal chances.}) 7... e5 {This was the idea of
Black's previous move.} 8. d5 Nd4 9. Nxd4 {The main move. Definitely, the best
way to fight for the advantage with White.} ({White has plenty of other
options, but none of them is giving White the advantage:} 9. Be3 Ng4 $1 {
[%csl Re3] Winning an important tempo.} 10. Bd2 Qh4 $5 {I like this idea.} ({
The alternative is also good enough.} 10... f5 11. f3 Nf6 12. exf5 Nxe2+ 13.
Qxe2 gxf5 14. Kh1 Bd7 $13 {[%cal Gg8h8,Gd8e8,Ge8g6] Black has a decent chances.
}) 11. h3 Nf6 {[%cal Gc8h3]} 12. f3 {One of the few ways to stop Black's
threats.} Nxe2+ ({If} 12... Nh5 {then} 13. Qe1) 13. Nxe2 Bh6 $1 {Exchanging
the black squared bishops here is a fine positional idea.} 14. Bxh6 Qxh6 15.
