{[%evp 0,11,19,31,14,-14,43,32,42,45,37,39,39,-3]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 {A tricky move order. Avoids Bg4 after Nf3 and also gives
White extra options after short castle.} (5. h4 {Is also an option. May
transpose to 5.Be20-06.h4, but also White has an extra idea.} O-O 6. h5 $5 {
A bit rare, but leads to very sharp and complicated positions.} (6. Be2 {
Transpose}) 6... Nxh5 {Black must take the pawn.} 7. g4 ({Worse is:} 7. Be2 Nf6
8. Bg5 Nbd7 9. Qd2 Re8 10. Bh6 Bh8 $15 {[%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] I don't see where
is White's attack.}) (7. Rxh5 $6 {This simply does not work here.} gxh5 8. Qxh5
f5 9. Bd3 Qe8 $17 {White has no full compensation.}) 7... Nf6 8. g5 Nfd7 9. f4
{White sacrificed a pawn but gained a lot of space in the centre. I think
objectively the game is very complicated. Of course, Black should be fine, but
still, both sides should play accurately.} Re8 $5 $146 {[%cal Gd7f8,Ge7e5,
Gc7c5] A logical improvement. Prepares e5 or c5, but also gives Black the
option to protect the pawn on h7 by Nf8.} 10. Be3 c5 {[%cal Gg7a1] Is better
than e5. Black wants to keep the diagonal a1-h8 to be open for his bishop.} 11.
d5 b5 12. cxb5 a6 $13 {The game is very complicated.}) 5... O-O 6. h4 {A very
modern way to play. This line is definitely very promising for White.
Sometimes to avoid Grunfeld some players even start with 11.d4Nf62.c4g63.h4,
then Black has the choice to transfer to King's Indian defence by 3...Bg74.
Nc30-05.e4d66.Be2.} c5 $1 {Clearly the best plan against this set-up. All
other options are dubious for Black. For example:} (6... e5 $6 7. d5 h5 8. Bg5
$16 {[%cal Gf2f3]}) 7. d5 {Here Black has a choice. To play 7...e6 in a Benoni
style,or 7...b5 Transferring the game into a Benko Gambit type of position.} b5
$5 {I prefer the Benko Gambit! A bit more rare compared to 7...e6.} (7... e6 {
Also a very possible, and more popular line. The position after:} 8. h5 exd5 9.
exd5 Re8 10. h6 $1 {A very important move! It is a bit awkward to put the pawn
there, but Black's problem is that his position is very passive, and there is
almost no counterplay.} Bh8 11. Bg5 {[%csl Gg5,Gh6] There are some high-level
games in this position. I believe Black still has to play very accurately.}) 8.
cxb5 a6 9. a4 {The best. The other options are:} (9. h5 $6 {Not a good idea.
Black is slightly better after:} axb5 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Bxb5 Nxe4 $1 12. Nxe4
Qa5+ 13. Nc3 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Qxb5 $15 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gb5c4,Gc8a6] White's
king is in more danger.}) (9. b6 {Not dangerous at all.} Qxb6 10. h5 Nbd7 11.
h6 ({If} 11. hxg6 {then very interesting is:} fxg6 $5 (11... hxg6 {Also good.})
12. Nf3 Ng4 $132 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gf8f2,Gd7e5] Black has the initiative.})
11... Bh8 12. Nf3 Rb8 $132 {[%cal Gf6g4] Black has a nice game.}) (9. bxa6 Qa5
10. Bd2 Bxa6 11. h5 {The only way to create some threats.} Bxe2 12. Ngxe2 Nxh5
13. Rxh5 {White must go all in.} gxh5 14. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f5,Gd1h5] White has
compensation, but Black also has his play. For example:} Nd7 15. Nf5 ({Another
option is:} 15. Qxh5 Rfb8 16. Nf5 Ne5 17. Qg5 Ng6 $132) ({Worse is:} 15. Nxh5
Ne5 {[%csl Ge5]}) 15... Ne5 16. Nxe7+ Kh8 $132 {With a very sharp and
complicated game.}) (9. Bd2 {This usually transpose to 9.a4.} axb5 10. Bxb5 Ba6
11. a4 {Transpose to the main line}) 9... axb5 ({Much worse is:} 9... Qa5 $6
10. Bd2 axb5 (10... Qb4 11. Qc2) 11. Nxb5 Qb6 12. Qc2 $16 {With a clear
advantage.}) 10. Bxb5 Ba6 {White has a choice here. To take on a6 or to let
Bxb5 ab5.} 11. Bxa6 {Maybe objectively the best.} ({More played is:} 11. Bd2
Bxb5 ({Maybe Black can also start with} 11... Qb6 $5) 12. axb5 Rxa1 13. Qxa1
Nbd7 {Black's plan is simple. Qb6-Rb-Ne8-c7 to try to return the pawn back.}
14. Nf3 (14. Nge2 {The knight here is a bit worse.} Qc7 15. O-O Nb6 $44 {
[%cal Gb6c4,Gf8a8]}) 14... Qb6 15. O-O Rb8 {[%cal Gf6e8,Ge8c7]} 16. Qa6 Ne8 17.
Ra1 Kf8 $44 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge8c7,Gg7c3] This position occurred in the game
Vachier Lagrave, M (2751) -Svidler,P (2714) Saint Louis 2021. I believe Black
has equal chances.}) (11. f3 {Protects the pawn on e4 but anyway is a very
strange move.} Qb6 12. Nge2 c4 $132 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gb6g1] White will not
castle soon.}) 11... Nxa6 12. Nf3 {The knight from f3 controls more squares.} (
12. Nge2 Qa5 13. O-O Rfb8 $44) 12... Qd7 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gd7g4] Normally the
queen goes to a5, but in this case, the intention is the square g4.} 13. O-O
Nb4 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gb4d3] Threats c4-Nd3.} ({Worse is:} 13... Rfb8 $6 {in view of
} 14. e5 $1) 14. Qe2 h6 $5 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gc1g5] A nice prophylactic move.
White has no good waiting moves.} 15. Bf4 Qg4 {[%csl Gg4] The queen here is
untouchable. The knight on f3 should always protect the pawn on h4.} 16. Bh2
Nd7 $44 {[%csl Gb4,Gg4][%cal Gf8b8] Black has a very nice compensation for the
pawn. The game remains very complicated and sharp.} *

