{[%evp 0,18,27,16,32,0,42,44,44,34,44,43,43,35,59,35,35,35,29,29,56]} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O {The classical system.
Black has a very big choice here. The main move for ages has been 7...Nc6. The
problem is that White has a lot of very interesting lines there. I believe the
Bayonete variation, which comes after 8.d5 Ne7 9.b4, is the most unpleasant
for Black. I think objectively White is better there. Of course, there is a
lot of there, but the latest games and the analyses are showing that Black has
a lot of problems. The other main line is 7...Na6. In my opinion the move 8.
Re1 is quite unpleasant for Black. The other big move is 7...Nbd7 in which
both 8. Re1 and 8.Be3 are very good for White. In all this lines there is a
lot of theory, but the theory and the latest games are showing that Black is
struggling.} exd4 $5 {This is the line that I suggest for you in this course.
This is the second most played move. 7...ed4 always has been one of the main
moves, but it was considered to be a little passive. In the last few years,
this move improved a lot. Very strong players tried it mainly in rapid and
blitz chess. I believe objectively is definitely one of the best moves. With
the latest games and my analysis, I am convinced that Black has decent chances
in this line. Another thing I like in this line is that the theory is much
less than 7...Nc6 and 7...Na6. Of course, you should remember some concrete
lines, but White has fewer options.} 8. Nxd4 Re8 9. f3 c6 $5 {[%cal Gd6d5]
This move came back in life in the last 2 years. Some years ago it was
considered to be dubious for Black. Mainly because of the games of M.Carlsen,
D.Dubov and M. Chigaev this line is once again playable. This is very similar
to the 7.Be3 line, but here is obvious that is a better version for White
because the bishop is not on e3 and White has the option to place the bishop
on g5 or f4.} ({Another main move is:} 9... Nc6 10. Be3 Nh5 {I think this line
is also playable, but a bit passive, and White always keep a small plus
